   =20
      Peak pod
   =20
 =20

The most basic   move in     finance is the   slicing of cash flows. You ha=
ve a thing with some uncertain payoff: It will surely be worth at least $X,=
 but it could be worth as much as $Y. You put the thing in a box and sell c=
laims on the box to different people who want different things. You sell $X=
 worth of senior claims to people who want safety, promising to pay them ba=
ck first: The box will surely be worth at least $X, so their claims are ver=
y safe. And then you sell some junior claims to other people who want risk:=
 The box could be worth as much as $Y, in which case you=E2=80=99d pay off =
the $X of senior claims and have money left over for the junior claims. Tho=
se claims are risky (they could go to zero), but also more lucrative (they =
could be worth a lot); they promise a higher expected return in exchange fo=
r taking more risk. And of course you could slice more finely: Issue one se=
t of super-safe senior claims, another set of pretty safe mezzanine claims,=
 a set of risky junior claims, etc. And an important way to come up with ne=
w financial businesses is to notice some financial thing with some fluctuat=
ing value and decompose it into a safe part and a risky part.=C2=A0
One way to think about multi-manager, multi-strategy   hedge funds (or =E2=
=80=9Cpod shops=E2=80=9D) is that they are a way to turn=C2=A0investing ski=
ll=C2=A0into this sort of tractable, tranche-able financial asset. The roug=
h theory is:
=09Some people can, with hard work and=C2=A0native skill, identify which st=
ocks (bonds, commodities, etc.) are better and which are worse, within some=
 narrow sector, with some reasonably high success rate. Not through any sor=
t of magic market intuition but through deep study and specialization: If y=
ou spend your life studying the biotech industry, you might have somewhat b=
etter-than-chance odds of picking which biotech stocks will outperform and =
which will underperform.=09If they just went out and bought the five stocks=
 they thought were the best, they=E2=80=99d have a good chance of making a =
lot of money, but there=E2=80=99d be risks too. Perhaps there would be a ge=
neral stock market crash, or a collapse in the biotech industry; they might=
 have accurately picked the best stocks but those stocks would still go dow=
n.=09But you can hire them and=C2=A0isolate their skill: Make them buy the =
best stocks in their sector, short the worst stocks in their sector, and ke=
ep a neutral exposure to the stock market, the sector and other factors, so=
 that they only make (or lose) money if their favorite stocks outperform (o=
r underperform) their least-favorite stocks due to their pure stock-picking=
 skill.=C2=A0=09And you can also hire other specialists in other sectors, a=
nd other asset classes, and make all of them hedge, so that you have a dive=
rsified portfolio that has no exposure to the broad stock market, to indivi=
dual sectors, to factors, etc., but is exposed only to their collective inv=
esting skill.=09And you fire the ones who mess up, so the overall skill lev=
el remains high.=09And then you decompose what they are doing into (1) a ve=
ry large, very boring, very safe portfolio and (2) a smaller and more volat=
ile stream of payoffs for their investing skill.

If you do this right, you can have them build a very large portfolio with n=
ot very much risk. They can bet on a lot of things, and bet against a lot o=
f other things, and those things are highly correlated with each other. Lik=
e, they make $1 billion of bets that blue widgets will go up, and they make=
 $1 billion of bets that green widgets will go down, and historically blue =
and green widget prices have moved in lockstep. That=E2=80=99s a total of $=
2 billion of bets, but they cancel each other out.
  [2]
 If blue widgets go down 20% (and they lose $200 million on their long bet)=
, then probably green widgets will also go down 20% (and they make $200 mil=
lion on their short bet), so there=E2=80=99s still $2 billion. But the idea=
 is that they know something the market doesn=E2=80=99t, and actually blue =
widgets will go up by 5=C2=A0percentage points more (or down by 5=C2=A0perc=
entage points less) than green widgets, and so they=E2=80=99ll make $50 mil=
lion on this bet. Of course they could be wrong; maybe blue widgets will=C2=
=A0underperform=C2=A0green ones and the bet will lose money. Not the whole =
$2 billion amount of the bet =E2=80=94=C2=A0blue and green widgets are pret=
ty fungible =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, you know, maybe $50 million.
And you can kind of abstractly do some math like =E2=80=9Cthis bet requires=
 $2 billion, and we hope it will pay back like $2.05=C2=A0billion, but even=
 if we=E2=80=99re wrong it should pay back $2 billion, or $1.95 billion at =
absolute worst.=E2=80=9D And then you can go out and sell, say, $1.9 billio=
n of senior claims on this bet, saying =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll pay you back =
the $1.9 billion no matter what.=E2=80=9D And then you raise, say, $100 mil=
lion of junior claims on this bet, saying =E2=80=9Cwe hope to pay you back =
$150 million on your $100 million investment, but if we=E2=80=99re wrong yo=
u eat the losses.=E2=80=9D
Traditionally the people buying the senior claims are prime brokerage desks=
 at big investment banks, and they can check all of this: They can look at =
the actual trades that you=E2=80=99re doing and say =E2=80=9Cah yes, histor=
ically, blue and green widget prices have been highly correlated, so the ch=
ances of losing much of this $2 billion is slim, and the chances of eating =
into our $1.9 billion are close to zero.=E2=80=9D And they can check=C2=A0 =
your track record, too, and say =E2=80=9Cyeah these guys usually make money=
 and always pay back their senior claims so it=E2=80=99s fine.=E2=80=9D Als=
o they hold your collateral =E2=80=94=C2=A0the blue widgets you=E2=80=99re =
long, the green widgets you=E2=80=99re short =E2=80=94=C2=A0and if the trad=
e does start to collapse they can probably shut it down before you lose too=
 much money (and, thus, before=C2=A0they=C2=A0lose=C2=A0any money).=C2=A0
And then traditionally the people buying the junior claims are your hedge f=
und investors, who are betting that you really do have all this investing s=
kill, that you really can turn their $100 million into $150 million much mo=
re often than you turn it into $50 million.
  [3]
=C2=A0And then traditionally you yourself, and your employees, have some so=
rt of super-junior claim, where you get paid a big chunk of the upside if t=
he bets pay off.
Now, another important move in finance is to worry about this slicing of ca=
sh flows. The traditional worries are:
=09The safe senior claims: Are they really that safe? Do we really=C2=A0kno=
w=C2=A0that this trade can=E2=80=99t lose a lot of money and cut into the $=
1.9 billion senior claim? What if blue widgets fall 10% and green widgets g=
o up 10%? Then this strategy loses $200 million, the junior claims are wipe=
d out and the lenders lose money.=09The risky junior claims: Boy, they sure=
 look risky! In the example above, the total portfolio lost 10% of its valu=
e, but the junior claims lost 100% of their value. Seems risky.=09The inter=
play between them:=C2=A0If you have a $2 billion portfolio and it loses 10%=
 of its value for some temporary reason, you might just hold onto it until =
the prices recover. But if you have a $2 billion portfolio with 95% leverag=
e and it loses 10% of its value, your lender =E2=80=94=C2=A0a bank prime br=
okerage =E2=80=94=C2=A0will seize the collateral and sell it as quickly as =
possible, which means (1) you permanently lose all of your equity and also =
(2) your lender=E2=80=99s sale might further drive down prices and cause mo=
re problems.

Here=E2=80=99s a   Bloomberg News story about =E2=80=9Cpeak pod=E2=80=9D:

Multimanager funds like [Ken] Griffin=E2=80=99s Citadel have come to domina=
te the hedge fund industry, riding a steady run of outperformance to overse=
e more than $1 trillion, including a healthy dose of leverage. But the expl=
osive growth has led the industry giants to pile into many of the same trad=
es.
That has built unease among regulators, investors and traders over these so=
-called pod shops. =E2=80=A6
Overcrowding in some bets, increased market volatility, an expensive talent=
 war and lower returns this year have prompted market=C2=A0participants=C2=
=A0to question whether the world of high finance is approaching peak pod. .=
..
=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s some overcrowding and concern about the amount of =
leverage at individual firms and collectively,=E2=80=9D John Jackson, head =
of hedge fund research at investment consultant Mercer, said during a recen=
t Capital Allocators podcast. And because they typically cut risk very quic=
kly =E2=80=9Cwe are worried about the potential snowball effect.=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=A6
Clients are now fixated on leverage and the risk of =E2=80=9Cplatform de-gr=
ossing=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 or stampede selling =E2=80=94 Goldman Sachs said =
in an earlier report. =E2=80=A6
Much of the increased regulatory focus has been in Treasury markets, where =
leverage tends to be the highest. Hedge funds in aggregate had estimated le=
verage of 56-to-1 on $553 billion of Treasury repo borrowing as of December=
 2022, according to a September research note by Federal Reserve staffers A=
yelen Banegas and Phillip Monin.
That=E2=80=99s why many of the big firms incurred larger-than-expected loss=
es during the early days of the Covid-19 pandemic. They were caught in the =
so-called basis trade, which is designed to profit from small differences b=
etween Treasury futures and the cash market. Considered a safe arbitrage be=
t if held to maturity, it can occasionally go haywire, as it did in March 2=
020.=C2=A0

If you are=20
long $1 billion of Treasury bonds and short $1 billion of Treasury futures,=
 your chances of losing even 2% of your money are low enough =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0because Treasury bonds and Treasury futures are almost the same thing =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0that a bank will lend you 98% of the money you need to do th=
at trade.
  [4]
=C2=A0But they are not zero! Sometimes bad stuff happens.
But the other problem is the crowded trades. =E2=80=9COf the $90.7 billion =
that Citadel held in US stocks at the end of September, 93% was in shares M=
illennium also holds,=E2=80=9D says the article. The essential bet of the m=
ulti-manager pod shops is that investing skill is (1) real, repeatable and =
identifiable and (2) not correlated to broad markets: Picking the better th=
ings and shorting the worse things should work whether the stock market is =
up and down. But the risk is that investing skill might be=C2=A0correlated =
with everyone else=E2=80=99s investing skill. If you hire people who are re=
ally good at knowing which stocks are good and which are bad, and then your=
 four biggest competitors hire similarly skilled people, they might all pic=
k the same good stocks and short the same bad stocks. And then if their bet=
s blow up, they all blow up at once.

 =20
   =20
      First-loss funds
   =20
 =20

Here=E2=80=99s another way to   slice the returns from hedge-fund skill:

Andrew Lubin, previously the chief executive officer of the London unit of =
SAC Capital Advisors, and=C2=A0Tim Pearey, former CEO of Odey Asset Managem=
ent, said they have started a hedge fund that provides capital to traders i=
f they put in their own cash and agree to lose their money first when bets =
fail.
Such arrangements, known as first-loss funds, are a niche part of the $4 tr=
illion hedge fund industry and offer traders an opportunity to hold on to m=
ore of their profits in exchange for taking on the bulk of the risk. Trader=
s signing up for Lubin and Pearey=E2=80=99s London-based AB Asset Scale cou=
ld keep as much as 60% of the profits they generate, higher than traditiona=
l industry payouts of 20% at major multi-strategy hedge funds. ...
Such platforms frequently hire and fire traders whose performance has dropp=
ed or when a trading strategy they run falls out of favour. Lubin and Peare=
y said they are looking to pick talented traders affected by this churn.
The first-loss funds provide as much as nine times the capital of a hedge f=
und or a trader, with their money being housed in a separately managed acco=
unt. The arrangement, which provides a significant boost to assets under ma=
nagement, requires any losses to accrue to the trader=E2=80=99s own investe=
d capital first. =E2=80=A6
Losses of up to 10% will be absorbed by the trader=E2=80=99s own capital wi=
th the fund aiming to liquidate their bets when declines hit 8.5%, accordin=
g to an investor document seen by Bloomberg.

I like it. The traditional way to get fired from a multi-manager fund is to=
 have too big a drawdown, to lose, say, 5% or 10% of your allocated capital=
. If you work at a big multi-strategy fund and then are =E2=80=9Caffected b=
y this churn,=E2=80=9D the natural inferences to draw are:
=09You have investing skill (that=E2=80=99s why the pod shop hired you), bu=
t=09You sometimes lose 10% of your capital (that=E2=80=99s why they fired y=
ou).

So someone else should be willing to hire you to run their money, but only =
if you take the risk of losing 10% of your capital.

 =20
   =20
      New OpenAI board
   =20
 =20

One  piece of news is that Microsoft Corp. will have a non-voting observer =
seat on the new board of directors of OpenAI. The problem, when OpenAI=E2=
=80=99s board=20
briefly fired Chief Executive Officer Sam Altman, was that Microsoft didn=
=E2=80=99t know about it in advance. Once Microsoft heard about Altman=E2=
=80=99s firing, it took, like, four days to get him his job back; that was =
not all Microsoft=E2=80=99s doing, but Microsoft clearly had something to d=
o with it. =E2=80=9CThe investors don=E2=80=99t exactly need a board seat i=
f they have a practical veto over the board=E2=80=99s biggest decisions,=E2=
=80=9D=20
I wrote yesterday,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cand the events of the last two weeks sugge=
st that they do.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
On the other hand it is inconvenient and disruptive that Microsoft had to e=
ffectively veto Altman=E2=80=99s firing after it happened? Better to be tol=
d first and head it off. Thus, board observer.
Here=E2=80=99s  one other piece of news, sort of, about the new board chair=
, Bret Taylor, =E2=80=9Cthe former co-CEO of business-software giant Salesf=
orce who also was the chairman of Twitter when it dealt with Elon Musk=E2=
=80=99s ultimately successful takeover effort=E2=80=9D:

OpenAI=E2=80=99s board is unusual in that it isn=E2=80=99t obligated to max=
imize shareholder value, but rather to fulfill a larger mission of advancin=
g artificial intelligence for humanity=E2=80=99s benefit. On its website, O=
penAI says the board=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cprincipal beneficiary is humanity, =
not OpenAI investors.=E2=80=9D
Asked if OpenAI=E2=80=99s board could revisit this structure, Taylor said: =
=E2=80=9CI think it=E2=80=99s a great question=E2=80=94probably not one for=
 my first day on the job.=E2=80=9D

That=E2=80=99s one possible answer! I mean, I guess technically it=E2=80=99=
s a non-answer, but it=E2=80=99s an interesting one.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CShould y=
ou benefit humanity or your investors?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CGreat question, no=
t sure yet.=E2=80=9D There are other possible answers! =E2=80=9CNo, the non=
profit structure is at the core of what we do, this company is fundamentall=
y about benefiting humanity, that=E2=80=99s what the investors and employee=
s signed up for,=C2=A0and that part is really nonnegotiable=E2=80=9D is, fo=
r instance, an imaginable answer. You could imagine the old nonprofit board=
, as a condition of letting Altman back, demanding =E2=80=9Clook you can br=
ing in new, more commercial directors, but the nonprofit structure has to s=
tay.=E2=80=9D But they ... didn=E2=80=99t do that? Apparently? And Taylor i=
s, like, for-profit-curious?
Incidentally, when Taylor and the Twitter Inc. board agreed to sell to Musk=
,   I wrote a column about how the board made and described that decision. =
What was striking, to me, was that Twitter=E2=80=99s then-CEO, Parag Agrawa=
l, described the decision to sell as=C2=A0purely=C2=A0doing what was in the=
 best interests of shareholders, without any consideration of the product, =
the mission, the employees, etc. Agrawal  said to employees:
=E2=80=9CThis is the answer you don=E2=80=99t want to hear, right?=E2=80=9D=
 Agrawal said. =E2=80=9CTwitter is a public company owned by shareholders. =
There are other companies which may have other legal mechanics =E2=80=A6 Tw=
itter is not one of those companies.=E2=80=9D
That is partly true, but not entirely true, and kind of grim. I wrote:
A lot of people think of Twitter as a public utility, a public trust, =E2=
=80=9Cthe town square,=E2=80=9D a company with an important social mission =
that many of its users and employees=C2=A0and Elon Musk=C2=A0care about dee=
ply. And its CEO and board of directors essentially can=E2=80=99t bring the=
mselves to talk about it. When employees asked him about what was best for =
the company, Agrawal could talk only about the shareholders. Elon Musk is n=
ot at all embarrassed to say that Twitter has an important public mission, =
which is why he=E2=80=99s buying it. But its current management can=E2=80=
=99t say that, which is why they=E2=80=99re selling it.
And now the chairman of the Twitter board that sold to Musk is the chairman=
 of OpenAI. Which definitely=C2=A0does=C2=A0have other legal mechanics. For=
 now.

