10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Cole Capital</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/33537957.286427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMTUvd2V3b3JrLXMtcmVzY3VlLXdhc24tdC1yZWFsP2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDExMzAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTEzMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB8ce19e2e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  talked a couple of weeks ago</a> about a fake pre=
ss release from a fake company called =E2=80=9CCole Capital Funds=E2=80=9D =
pretending it would buy WeWork Inc. for $9 per share. The press release wen=
t out a little after 5 p.m. on Friday, Nov. 3; WeWork filed for bankruptcy =
the following Monday. I proposed two possible reasons someone might put out=
 that press release:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Market manipulation: You buy some WeW=
ork stock cheap, you pretend someone will buy the company at $9, the stock =
goes up, you sell at a profit.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Gen=
eral fun and hijinks: Some people just like pretending to buy companies?</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean! The first explanation is overwhelmingl=
y more probable.=C2=A0The only objection to it, really, is that the press r=
elease went out at 5 p.m. on a Friday. The market was closed. By the time t=
he market opened for trading again on Monday, (1) everyone knew the press r=
elease was fake and (2) anyway WeWork was bankrupt and the stock was halted=
. =E2=80=9CIf you want to manipulate the stock and make a profit,=E2=80=9D =
I wrote in a not-legal-advice fashion,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cdo your press release =
at like 9:31 a.m. on a Monday, so you can trade on it for a bit.=E2=80=9D</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I missed an obvious third explanation, whi=
ch is =E2=80=9Cmarket manipulation, but incompetent.=E2=80=9D I <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33537957.286427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDYtMDQvZ3V5LXdoby1kaWQt=
YXZvbi1ob2F4LXdhcy10ZXJyaWJsZS1hdC1ob2F4ZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEzMDIzX01PTkVZU1R=
VRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMT=
MwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB71b46749" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">  wrote once</a> about a guy named Nedko Nedev, who allegedly issued a s=
eries of fake press releases pretending to acquire various public companies=
, for straightforward market manipulation reasons: He would buy the stock, =
he=E2=80=99d put out the press release, the stock would pop, and he=E2=80=
=99d sell it. The problem is that he kept waiting too long to sell, and los=
t money on each trade.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; b=
ackground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It is possible that the people who do this sort of (extremely pub=
lic, not that hard to catch) market manipulation are not very good at it?</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Patrick Clark ha=
d <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33537957.286427/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMjkvc2VjLXN=
heXMtd2V3b3JrLW9wdGlvbnMtcGxvdC1mYWlsZWQtb24tYm90Y2hlZC1wcmVzcy1yZWxlYXNlP2=
NtcGlkPUJCRDExMzAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZ=
XdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTEzMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cBb213cc5e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  an update on Cole Capital</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The US Securities and Exchange Commission accu=
sed a strip mall owner of a botched attempt to profit by manipulating the p=
rice of WeWork Inc. shares and using client funds to pay for his lavish lif=
estyle.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The real estate investor, Jonathan Larmore, wa=
s behind an entity called Cole Capital that made an offer to buy WeWork sto=
ck at a large premium earlier this month, in the days before the coworking =
company filed Chapter 11 bankruptcy. The move briefly sent the shares soari=
ng, according to the SEC complaint filed in Arizona.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Larmore had previously acquired call option co=
ntracts on WeWork stock, meaning he stood to make =E2=80=9Chundreds of thou=
sands to millions of dollars,=E2=80=9D according to the SEC, but he alleged=
ly mistimed the press release.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CHis options expired just over an hour=
 before the WeWork stock price spiked as a result of his manipulative condu=
ct,=E2=80=9D the complaint said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are the SEC=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33537957.286427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjL=
mdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy0yNDI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB38a9383=
b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> announcement</a> and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/33537957.286427/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudH=
MvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JpOUpfSThCNGdyRS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8=
a271037" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">complaint</a>, which are=C2=A0mostly about other, less fun=
ny frauds that Larmore also allegedly did. But the WeWork stuff includes th=
e traditional purchase of short-dated out-of-the-money call options:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On or about November 1 and November 2, 2023, L=
armore purchased a total of 72,846 call option contracts on the common stoc=
k of the publicly-traded company WeWork, the common stock of which is sold =
under the ticker symbol =E2=80=9CWE=E2=80=9D on the NASDAQ National Market,=
 for $0.03 to $0.15 per contract. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The expiration date for the vast majority of t=
he WeWork call options was November 3, 2023, at 4:00 p.m. EDT. A smaller po=
rtion had an expiration date of November 10, 2023, at 4:00 p.m. EDT. =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The strike prices for the WeWork call options =
Larmore purchased ranged from $2 to $5. Having purchased the out-of-the mon=
ey call options for pennies per contract, Larmore stood to make substantial=
 gains if the stock price rose above the strike price of some or all of the=
 options.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Followed by, uh, emailing the SEC to manipulat=
e the stock?</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the morning of November 3, 2023=
, Larmore sent an email to an SEC mailbox from an email address at the Cole=
 Capital website. The email attached a document that Larmore was seeking to=
 file publicly with the SEC, identified as a=C2=A0=E2=80=9CSchedule TO.=E2=
=80=9D A Schedule TO is a filing required to be made with the SEC by a pers=
on who intends to make a =E2=80=9Ctender offer=E2=80=9D for securities regi=
stered under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also the press release:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On November 3, at 5:12 p.m. EDT, a=
 Cole Capital press release was disseminated through a wire service and pic=
ked up by several media sites. Larmore arranged to send out the release thr=
ough the wire service, and he paid for its publication. Larmore had submitt=
ed the release to the service well before the close of trading hours that d=
ay, but the service had rejected it at least once for formatting issues or =
other irregularities.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, womp womp:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Although at the close of market trading (4:00 =
p.m. EDT) on November 3, 2023, WeWork=E2=80=99s stock price closed at $0.83=
 per share, immediately after the press release was published, the share pr=
ice of WeWork jumped in afterhours trading to $1.45 per share, and reached =
a high that evening of $2.14 per share, at 6:31 p.m. EDT. Most websites tha=
t had posted the press release removed it by the next morning. The stock pr=
ice closed at $1.18 at the end of afterhours trading.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Larmore did not exercise his November 3 call o=
ptions because they had expired before the press release was published, and=
 he did not exercise his November 10 call options because the stock price d=
id not exceed the strike price. Indeed, on Monday, November 6, 2023, WeWork=
 filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Should=C2=A0</em>you email the SEC if you =
are planning to put out a fake press release about a fake tender offer? I g=
uess it doesn=E2=80=99t matter much either way. They can see the press rele=
ase. I suppose you can argue =E2=80=9Cno, this was a real offer, as you can=
 see because I emailed the SEC about it,=E2=80=9D but they=E2=80=99re not g=
oing to believe that. =E2=80=9CLarmore and Cole Capital did not have suffic=
ient liquid capital to execute Cole Capital=E2=80=99s proposed tender offer=
,=E2=80=9D says the SEC, and obviously buying all those options first is su=
spicious. Really the not-legal-advice lesson here is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0make su=
re you have the formatting right before you try to publish your fake merger=
 press release?=C2=A0</p>
