rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  slicing</a> of cash flows. You have a t=
hing with some uncertain payoff: It will surely be worth at least $X, but i=
t could be worth as much as $Y. You put the thing in a box and sell claims =
on the box to different people who want different things. You sell $X worth=
 of senior claims to people who want safety, promising to pay them back fir=
st: The box will surely be worth at least $X, so their claims are very safe=
. And then you sell some junior claims to other people who want risk: The b=
ox could be worth as much as $Y, in which case you=E2=80=99d pay off the $X=
 of senior claims and have money left over for the junior claims. Those cla=
ims are risky (they could go to zero), but also more lucrative (they could =
be worth a lot); they promise a higher expected return in exchange for taki=
ng more risk. And of course you could slice more finely: Issue one set of s=
uper-safe senior claims, another set of pretty safe mezzanine claims, a set=
 of risky junior claims, etc. And an important way to come up with new fina=
ncial businesses is to notice some financial thing with some fluctuating va=
lue and decompose it into a safe part and a risky part.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to think about multi-manager, multi-st=
rategy <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33537957.28=
6427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMD=
gvdGhlLWNvZmZlZS1mdXR1cmVzLWdvdC1zdGFsZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTMwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGR=
iZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzExMzAm=
dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8762b40f" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  hedge funds</a> (or =E2=80=9Cpod shops=E2=80=9D) is that they are a way t=
o turn=C2=A0<em>investing skill=C2=A0</em>into this sort of tractable, tran=
che-able financial asset. The rough theory is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some people can, with hard work and=
=C2=A0native skill, identify which stocks (bonds, commodities, etc.) are be=
tter and which are worse, within some narrow sector, with some reasonably h=
igh success rate. Not through any sort of magic market intuition but throug=
h deep study and specialization: If you spend your life studying the biotec=
h industry, you might have somewhat better-than-chance odds of picking whic=
h biotech stocks will outperform and which will underperform.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If they just went out and bought the five stock=
s they thought were the best, they=E2=80=99d have a good chance of making a=
 lot of money, but there=E2=80=99d be risks too. Perhaps there would be a g=
eneral stock market crash, or a collapse in the biotech industry; they migh=
t have accurately picked the best stocks but those stocks would still go do=
wn.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But you can hire them and=C2=
=A0isolate their skill: Make them buy the best stocks in their sector, shor=
t the worst stocks in their sector, and keep a neutral exposure to the stoc=
k market, the sector and other factors, so that they only make (or lose) mo=
ney if their favorite stocks outperform (or underperform) their least-favor=
ite stocks due to their pure stock-picking skill.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">And you can also hire other specialists in other sect=
ors, and other asset classes, and make all of them hedge, so that you have =
a diversified portfolio that has no exposure to the broad stock market, to =
individual sectors, to factors, etc., but is exposed only to their collecti=
ve investing skill.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">And you fire t=
he ones who mess up, so the overall skill level remains high.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">And then you decompose what they are doing into=
 (1) a very large, very boring, very safe portfolio and (2) a smaller and m=
ore volatile stream of payoffs for their investing skill.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you do this right, you can have them build =
a very large portfolio with not very much risk. They can bet on a lot of th=
ings, and bet against a lot of other things, and those things are highly co=
rrelated with each other. Like, they make $1 billion of bets that blue widg=
ets will go up, and they make $1 billion of bets that green widgets will go=
 down, and historically blue and green widget prices have moved in lockstep=
. That=E2=80=99s a total of $2 billion of bets, but they cancel each other =
out.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> If blue widgets go down 20% (and they lose $200 million on their long =
bet), then probably green widgets will also go down 20% (and they make $200=
 million on their short bet), so there=E2=80=99s still $2 billion. But the =
idea is that they know something the market doesn=E2=80=99t, and actually b=
lue widgets will go up by 5=C2=A0percentage points more (or down by 5=C2=A0=
percentage points less) than green widgets, and so they=E2=80=99ll make $50=
 million on this bet. Of course they could be wrong; maybe blue widgets wil=
l=C2=A0<em>underperform=C2=A0</em>green ones and the bet will lose money. N=
ot the whole $2 billion amount of the bet =E2=80=94=C2=A0blue and green wid=
gets are pretty fungible =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, you know, maybe $50 million.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And you can kind of abstractly do some math li=
ke =E2=80=9Cthis bet requires $2 billion, and we hope it will pay back like=
 $2.05=C2=A0billion, but even if we=E2=80=99re wrong it should pay back $2 =
billion, or $1.95 billion at absolute worst.=E2=80=9D And then you can go o=
ut and sell, say, $1.9 billion of senior claims on this bet, saying =E2=80=
=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll pay you back the $1.9 billion no matter what.=E2=80=9D And=
 then you raise, say, $100 million of junior claims on this bet, saying =E2=
=80=9Cwe hope to pay you back $150 million on your $100 million investment,=
 but if we=E2=80=99re wrong you eat the losses.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traditionally the people buying the senior cla=
ims are prime brokerage desks at big investment banks, and they can check a=
ll of this: They can look at the actual trades that you=E2=80=99re doing an=
d say =E2=80=9Cah yes, historically, blue and green widget prices have been=
 highly correlated, so the chances of losing much of this $2 billion is sli=
m, and the chances of eating into our $1.9 billion are close to zero.=E2=80=
=9D And they can check=C2=A0 your track record, too, and say =E2=80=9Cyeah =
these guys usually make money and always pay back their senior claims so it=
=E2=80=99s fine.=E2=80=9D Also they hold your collateral =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
 blue widgets you=E2=80=99re long, the green widgets you=E2=80=99re short =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and if the trade does start to collapse they can probably sh=
ut it down before you lose too much money (and, thus, before=C2=A0<em>they=
=C2=A0</em>lose=C2=A0any money).=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then traditionally the people buying the j=
unior claims are your hedge fund investors, who are betting that you really=
 do have all this investing skill, that you really can turn their $100 mill=
ion into $150 million much more often than you turn it into $50 million.<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And then traditionally you yourself, and your employees, have som=
e sort of super-junior claim, where you get paid a big chunk of the upside =
if the bets pay off.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, another important move in finance is to w=
orry about this slicing of cash flows. The traditional worries are:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The safe senior claims: Are they real=
ly that safe? Do we really=C2=A0<em>know=C2=A0</em>that this trade can=E2=
=80=99t lose a lot of money and cut into the $1.9 billion senior claim? Wha=
t if blue widgets fall 10% and green widgets go up 10%? Then this strategy =
loses $200 million, the junior claims are wiped out and the lenders lose mo=
ney.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The risky junior claims: Boy,=
 they sure look risky! In the example above, the total portfolio lost 10% o=
f its value, but the junior claims lost 100% of their value. Seems risky.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The interplay between them:=C2=A0If=
 you have a $2 billion portfolio and it loses 10% of its value for some tem=
porary reason, you might just hold onto it until the prices recover. But if=
 you have a $2 billion portfolio with 95% leverage and it loses 10% of its =
value, your lender =E2=80=94=C2=A0a bank prime brokerage =E2=80=94=C2=A0wil=
l seize the collateral and sell it as quickly as possible, which means (1) =
you permanently lose all of your equity and also (2) your lender=E2=80=99s =
sale might further drive down prices and cause more problems.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/33537957.286427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMzAva2VuLWdyaWZmaW4tcy1jaXRhZGVsLWhlZGdlLW=
Z1bmQtcml2YWxzLWRyYXctc2NydXRpbnktb3Zlci1jcm93ZGluZy1sZXZlcmFnZT9jbXBpZD1CQ=
kQxMTMwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRl=
ciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzExMzAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB7124623c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  Bloomberg News story about =E2=80=9Cpeak pod=E2=
=80=9D</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Multimanager funds like [Ken] Griffin=E2=80=99=
s Citadel have come to dominate the hedge fund industry, riding a steady ru=
n of outperformance to oversee more than $1 trillion, including a healthy d=
ose of leverage. But the explosive growth has led the industry giants to pi=
le into many of the same trades.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That has built unease among regulators, invest=
ors and traders over these so-called pod shops. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Overcrowding in some bets, increased market vo=
latility, an expensive talent war and lower returns this year have prompted=
 market=C2=A0participants=C2=A0to question whether the world of high financ=
e is approaching peak pod. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s some overcrowding and=
 concern about the amount of leverage at individual firms and collectively,=
=E2=80=9D John Jackson, head of hedge fund research at investment consultan=
t Mercer, said during a recent Capital Allocators podcast. And because they=
 typically cut risk very quickly =E2=80=9Cwe are worried about the potentia=
l snowball effect.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Clients are now fixated on leverage and the ri=
sk of =E2=80=9Cplatform de-grossing=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 or stampede selling =
=E2=80=94 Goldman Sachs said in an earlier report. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Much of the increased regulatory focus has bee=
n in Treasury markets, where leverage tends to be the highest. Hedge funds =
in aggregate had estimated leverage of 56-to-1 on $553 billion of Treasury =
repo borrowing as of December 2022, according to a September research note =
by Federal Reserve staffers Ayelen Banegas and Phillip Monin.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s why many of the big firms incur=
red larger-than-expected losses during the early days of the Covid-19 pande=
mic. They were caught in the so-called basis trade, which is designed to pr=
ofit from small differences between Treasury futures and the cash market. C=
onsidered a safe arbitrage bet if held to maturity, it can occasionally go =
haywire, as it did in March 2020.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/33537957.286427/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMTQvcGVvcGxlLWFyZS13b3JyaWVkLWFib3V0LXRoZS1i=
YXNpcy10cmFkZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTMwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV=
0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzExMzAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3=
R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb66dc48d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
long $1 billion of Treasury bonds and short $1 billion of Treasury futures<=
/a>, your chances of losing even 2% of your money are low enough =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0because Treasury bonds and Treasury futures are almost the same thing=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0that a bank will lend you 98% of the money you need to do t=
hat trade.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But they are not zero! Sometimes bad stuff happens.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the other problem is the crowded trades. =
=E2=80=9COf the $90.7 billion that Citadel held in US stocks at the end of =
September, 93% was in shares Millennium also holds,=E2=80=9D says the artic=
le. The essential bet of the multi-manager pod shops is that investing skil=
l is (1) real, repeatable and identifiable and (2) not correlated to broad =
markets: Picking the better things and shorting the worse things should wor=
k whether the stock market is up and down. But the risk is that investing s=
kill might be=C2=A0<em>correlated with everyone else=E2=80=99s investing sk=
ill. </em>If you hire people who are really good at knowing which stocks ar=
e good and which are bad, and then your four biggest competitors hire simil=
arly skilled people, they might all pick the same good stocks and short the=
 same bad stocks. And then if their bets blow up, they all blow up at once.=
</p>
